        <h2>When I grow up I want to have a horse farm, but I don’t know how to start off. Can you give me a hint?</h2>

        <p>I can´t tell you how to do it, many girls dream about that, including me! It´s not all fun and games, there’s hard work involved. You have to learn about how to take care of animals, so a good start would include learning as much as you can about animals.</p>
        <p></p>


        <h2>How old were you when you rode a horse for the first time in your life?</h2>

        <p>I was 3-years-old when I first rode a horse. I started at a local riding school once every week. I loved horses from the first time a saw one and I know that I´ll always be involved with these wonderful animals.</p>

        
        <h2>I'm going to a horse summer camp, and I need some advice. I am a pretty good rider (can handle all gaits) and I want to learn at summer camp but it is a beginner camp, I know horse care and such so
what do I do? Tell them my riding experience or pretend to be a beginner?</h2>

        <p>It´s hard to say for how long you are a “beginner,” it depends on many things. I´m sure you are good with horses and that means a lot! Hopefully you can learn even more at summer camp.  When the camp is labeled “for beginners” it´s also got something to do with grownups taking responsibility for your well being. I hope you have a NICE summer camp.</p>

        <p>I also do dressage. I just love the feeling I get after riding a good dressage program.  If you have any suggestions for cards, please mail them.  I can´t promise that we will use your suggestions, but please mail them.</p>
		
